<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Climate models are not crystal balls. They're physics simulations on a grid.</p>
  <p>Every cell of the atmosphere has equations for radiation, fluid motion, water vapor, cloud formation. The smaller the cell, the more computation; the larger the cell, the more <strong>parametrisation</strong> (rules-of-thumb for sub-grid physics — what's happening inside a cell too big to simulate directly). Different models choose different parametrisations. That's why two models can disagree about a regional projection while both being "right" in some sense — they're answering slightly different versions of the question.</p>
  <p>By the end of today, you can decode the parts of an IPCC projection figure: the axes (what's being measured), the lines (which scenario), the shaded ranges (model spread or confidence interval), the confidence-level language ("likely" / "very likely" / "virtually certain"). By Block 7 you'll use this skill on Chennai-specific projections for your <a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Climate Brief's Evidence section</a>.</p>
  <p>One critical distinction the <a href="/ai-partners/climate-modeler/">Climate Modeler</a> will hold the line on: <strong>projection vs. prediction</strong>. Models project under specific scenario assumptions ("if emissions follow SSP5-8.5..."). They don't predict ("Chennai will see X mm of sea-level rise by 2050"). That distinction will appear on the rubric.</p>
</section>

